<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Xanden</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Disciple<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jan 2003<br />
	Location: San Jose, CA
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>As a longtime ranger, I've always paid close attention to dual wield.  Well, here's my understanding:<br />
<br />
1)  Every NPC in the game of the appropriate level will dual wield when given appropriate weapons.  Class doesn't matter.  Obviously, if they are holding something they like more, the weapon will just go into their inventory.<br />
<br />
2)  At one point, certain class pets after a certain level were given innate dual-wield and didn't need to equip their pets with weapons.  This seems to be mage/necro/enchanter/shadowknight pets only.  Haven't checked druid pets.<br />
<br />
3)  Our pets are 'standard mobs,' in that they cannot quad without weapons.  Relatively few mobs in the game are flagged as "quadders" and are able to dual-wield without weapons.  The other pets were flagged as "quadders" but not ours, obviously because we are not a "pet class."  Enchanter pets always start with a shield in their secondary, so we'll never know if they could dual wield without a second weapon.<br />
<br />
<br />
Possibility:  Our pets are animals, and as such their innate attack is "bite" and not "hit" like other pets.  It is possible that "animals" can never be "quadders," at least I have never seen a biter/clawer also quad.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />Xanden Ashenwolf, 56 Luminary<br />
Ainder Ashenwolf, 60 Outrider<br />
Xandain Ashdale, 57 Defiler</div>
	
	
